*sigh* I love the beach, and LBI and working down there, having fun being a moron and going crazy... but sometimes I wonder what it would be like to spend my whole summer in New Egypt - you know, being able to hang out with friends all the time. Going to concerts spontaneously, where it doesn't have to be planned three weeks in advance. I know I'm leaving tomorrow. I know I can't wait. But there's this little part of me inside that's nagging, 'you KNOW you want to stay home and hang out with the people you never see anymore - tara, lindsey, lisa.. you KNOW you want to. And you can't, because you've already signed your life away to the beach.' And it makes me sad inside to know that I can't hang out with these guys on a normal or even somewhat semi/pseudo-normal basis. I know the whole reason I go away is to leave New Egypt, to get away from it, because I dislike the place... but deep down it's really grown on me. It's become somewhat close to my heart and I don't want to leave... but I do. It's complicated like that.
I always tell people to come visit me, and they promise they will. I tell them where I work and give out my cell number and the shore phone, and it really hurts to realize on Labor Day weekend that they still haven't come and most likely won't be. It's happened a number of times, with many different people. And each time, it's someone who I would go find at their workplace at some point over the course of the summer, or at least call them and tell them, 'I hope you're having fun, but I'm sorry I'm not gunna make it down to see you... Have fun for me and I'll call you again.' I'd make up for it. I guess what it just comes down to is that I'm one of those people that takes promises to heart and really holds true to them. Sorry for being so generous and promise-upstanding.
I guess I'd better be going, as it's nearly eleven, I'm leaving at eight AM and I'm still not completely packed.

This was my one for the road.
-Courtney

None of the lists of what I did today. ========================================= it was a heart wrenching end to a perfect tale of love. She wept. He was silent. She blew her nose. He had offered her no handkerchief. She left. He stayed behind. She was never to see his face again. He could no longer open his eyes. She left him a single rose. He couldn't smell it or touch it or see it. She had once stayed behind. He had once left her. It was the cause of all this despair. He had been twenty. She was eighteen at the time. He didn't go to college, because he had no money. She was a shoo-in at Vassar thanks to her parents. He left for the US Marine Corps boot camp. She moved into her dorm on the same day. He had seen her the day before. She had been crying, missing him already. He had promised to marry her when he came back. She nodded and took his word for granted. He had smiled and taken her home. She had thrown her arms around his neck and wept some more. He soothed her, wrapping his arms around her. She had kissed him upon the lips, the most assertive move she'd ever made. He'd been surprised, but had kissed her back. She said, 'I love you.' He said it, too. 'I love you.' (Three simple words in an eight-letter phrase.) She didn't know where he went after a few weeks. He wasn't allowed to send letters, they might have been intercepted. She was worried sick about him. He thought about her night and day. She was ecstatic when she got the letter with her name written on it, in his handwriting. He had written to tell her how much he loved her, and that he expected to be home in a month. She looked at the date at the top. (April 30) He didn't come home. It was already June 27th. Two months had passed. She looked again at the pile of mail. It was typed, formal, and had 'Department of the Military' written as the return address. She couldn't breathe. She couldn't open it. She couldn't touch it. She fell down in a pile and wept. * He was silent, startched, and solemn. She thought he was sleeping. He had no warmth in his face when she touched it. She wished he were there for her, that it was anyone else. He had no sympathies or a shoulder for her to cry on. She wept. He was silent. She blew her nose. He had offered her no handkerchief. She left. He stayed behind. She was never to see his face again. He could no longer open his eyes. She left him a single rose. He couldn't smell it or touch it or see it. She touched the casket and walked away. He was dead and gone. In his death, her heart died, too. *** In remembrance of the loved ones lost in war. -I'm out... Comments are kindly welcomed
